<body>
    
        <section>
            <title>Relating Hypothesis Tests and Confidence Intervals</title>
            <body>
                <p>Just as we did for proportions, we may examine a confidence interval to decide
                    whether a proposed value of the population mean is plausible. </p>
                <p>Suppose we want to test <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:msub>
                                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                    </m:msub>
                                    <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                </m:mrow>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math> vs. <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mrow>
                                    <m:msub>
                                        <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                        <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                                    </m:msub>
                                    <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>≠</m:mo>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                </m:mrow>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math> using a significance level of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mi mathvariant="normal">α</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>05</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>. An alternative way to perform this test is to find a 95% confidence
                    interval for μ and make the following conclusions:</p>
                <p>If <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math> falls outside the confidence interval, reject H<sub>o</sub>.</p>
                <p>If <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:msub>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                            </m:msub>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math> falls inside the confidence interval, do not reject H<sub>o</sub>.</p>
                <example>
                    <p>We'll use example 2, in which the alternative was two-sided.</p>
                    <p>Recall that we want to check whether a medication conforms to a target
                        concentration of a chemical ingredient by testing</p>
                    <p>
                        <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:msub>
                                    <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                    <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                                </m:msub>
                                <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>250</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:msub>
                                    <m:mi>H</m:mi>
                                    <m:mi>a</m:mi>
                                </m:msub>
                                <m:mo>:</m:mo>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">μ</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>≠</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>250</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>
                    </p>
                    <p>We assume that <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>12</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>, and in a sample of size n = 100 we obtained a sample mean of
                            <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>247</m:mn>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>.</p>
                    <p>A 95% confidence interval for μ is <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mover>
                                    <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                                    <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                                </m:mover>
                                <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mi mathvariant="normal">σ</m:mi>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mi>n</m:mi>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mfrac>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>247</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                                <m:mfrac>
                                    <m:mn>12</m:mn>
                                    <m:msqrt>
                                        <m:mn>100</m:mn>
                                    </m:msqrt>
                                </m:mfrac>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>247</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                                <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                                <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                                <m:mfenced open="(" close=")">
                                    <m:mrow>
                                        <m:mn>244</m:mn>
                                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                                        <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                                        <m:mo>,</m:mo>
                                        <m:mtext> </m:mtext>
                                        <m:mn>249</m:mn>
                                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                                        <m:mn>4</m:mn>
                                    </m:mrow>
                                </m:mfenced>
                            </m:mrow>
                        </m:math>. </p>
                    <p>Since the interval does not contain 250, we reject H<sub>o</sub> and conclude
                        that the alternative is true: the population mean concentration differs from
                        250. </p>
                    <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image354.gif" alt="A number line showing
the 95% confidence interval, which is (244.6, 249.4). 250 is also marked on the number line, and it
isn't within the interval, so we can be confident that &mu; isn't 250. In other words, we can reject
the hypothesis H_0:&mu; = 250"/>
                </example>
            </body>
        </section>
